article.headline: Gophers freshman Roysland scores 14 in first start
article.story:
CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) -- Minnesota coach Pam Borton wants to make
something clear: Just because the No. 10 Golden Gophers lost
All-American Lindsay Whalen to a broken hand last week, they're not
giving up on the season.

"It's not going to be easy without Lindsay," Borton said.
"But I still think we can win the rest of our basketball games
this year."

Minnesota (19-4, 8-4 Big Ten) got off to a good start Sunday
with a 63-54 win over Illinois (10-13, 4-8). Shannon Bolden scored
18 points and freshman Kelly Roysland, making her first start,
added 14 to lead the Gophers.

"I think this is huge for us because we needed to know that we
could play without Lindsay and we could win without her," Roysland
said.

Roysland was 5-of-9 from the field, including 3-for-4 from
3-point range, while replacing Whalen in the starting lineup.

Whalen, a senior guard who became Minnesota's all-time leading
scorer earlier in the year, broke two bones in her right hand in
the Gophers' loss to Ohio State last Thursday.

Shannon Schonrock had 14 points for Minnesota.

Tiffanie Guthrie led Illinois with 24 points and 12 rebounds,
while Angelina Williams added 12 points and senior center Cindy
Dallas, the school's all-time leading rebounder, had 10 rebounds.

The Gophers led 26-24 after a sloppy first half in which they
committed 10 turnovers and limited Illinois to 31.3-percent
shooting from the field. The Illini's shooting got worse in the
second half, dropping to 24 percent, and they finished 17-of-61
from the field.

Minnesota had a 12-2 run that included three straight 3-pointers
-- two by Bolden -- that gave the Gophers a 44-35 lead with 7:57 to
play. Illinois never got closer than five points the rest of the
way.

"I don't know if we really played with the lead well today,"
Illini coach Theresa Grentz said. "I don't know if we were looking
over our shoulders. I don't think sometimes we really believe we
deserve to win."
